10. Optional - Optional class is a container object that may or may not contain a value. It was introduced as part of the import java.util.Optional; package to help
		developers avoid NullPointerExceptions and to provide a more expressive way to handle optional values.

	Creating an Optional: -You can create an Optional instance in several ways:
		1. Optional<String> opt = Optional.empty();					// creates an empty Optional instance, it does not contain a value
		2. Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("Hello, World!");		// creates an Optional with a value. If the value is null, it throws a NullPointerException.
		3. Optional<String> opt = Optional.ofNullable(null); 		// creates an Optional that can hold a value that may be null. If the value is null, it creates 
																	   an empty Optional.

	Common Methods of Optional  (OrElseGet flat IfPresent )
	1. isPresent(): Checks if a value is present. returns a boolean. it requires get(). it Can lead to NoSuchElementException. Not functional. Avoid using this method.
		Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Jamil");
		if (name.isPresent()) {
    			System.out.println(name.get()); 		// Prints: Jamil
		}
	
	2. ifPresent(Consumer<? super T> action): Executes a lambda only if a value is present. return void. doesnt require get(). it is functional. recommended to use.  
		name.ifPresent(value -> System.out.println(value)); 		// Prints: Jamil

	3. get(): Returns the value if present; otherwise, it throws NoSuchElementException.
		String value = name.get(); 			// Returns "Jamil"

	4. orElse(T other): Eager Evaluation. Returns the value if present; otherwise, returns the provided default value.  
		String result = name.orElse(getDefault()); 
		cons: getDefault() is called even though the value exists. This can cause Performance issues, Unintended side effects, Unnecessary DB or API calls.

	5. orElseGet(Supplier<? extends T> other): Lazy Evaluation, Returns the value if present; otherwise, invokes the provided supplier and returns the result.
		String result = name.orElseGet(() -> getDefault());
		pros: getDefault() executes only if Optional is Empty. 

	6. orElseThrow(Supplier<? extends X> exceptionSupplier): Returns the value if present; otherwise, throws an exception created by the provided supplier.
		Throws NoSuchElementException. Mostly useful for internal APIs.
		Optional<User> optUser = findUser();
		User user = optUser.orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("User not found"));

		Pros: Use orElseThrow() in service layer, ✅ Throw domain‑specific exceptions, ✅ Combine with global exception handling, ✅ Avoid parameterless orElseThrow() for APIs
			  ✅ Keep exception messages clear & actionable
		Avoid using Parameterless orElseThrow() in APIs.  example:  optional.orElseThrow();


	7. map(Function<? super T, ? extends U> mapper): Transforms the value & returns the result back into an Optional. if the original Optional is empty Returns Optional.empty() 
		Optional<Integer> lengthOfStr = name.map(String::length); 			// Returns Optional[5]

	8. flatMap(Function<? super T, Optional<U>> mapper): Similar to map, but the mapping function must return an Optional
		Optional<Integer> lengthOfStr = name.flatMap(value -> Optional.of(value.length())); // Returns Optional[5]

		Note: Use map() when the function returns a normal value
			  Use flatMap() when the function returns an Optional

