25. hashmap internal working
	when we write  map<String, Integer> mymap = new HashMap<>();   the following occurs. 
		1. A HashMap object is created, memory is allocated on the heap. Internal fields are initialized: size = 0, loadFactor = 0.75, table = null. It uses lazy
			initialization.  No table is created yet.
		2. Table is created only when the first put() happens. A bucket is a single index in the table array. table[0] → bucket 0, table[1] → bucket 1 
			example: myMap.put("a", 1);
			put(key, value) -> hash(key) -> initialize table if needed -> calculate index -> table empty? YES → insert node, NO → check equals? same key → replace,
			different key → chain / treeify. resize if needed.
			Now: Default capacity = 16, table of size 16 is created. we can have 1 null key whose index will be 0 in table.
		3. hashcode is generated for keys using "key.hashCode()" method. If key is null, hash is 0.
		4. index is generated  using this formula  "index = (n - 1) & hash".  Where n = array length (capacity, e.g., 16) and hash = key.hashCode().
		5. this index is used to determine location of the value to be stored in table.
		6. Node is a nested class within hashmap class. it represents one key–value pair. The node structure is like     [ hashcode, key, value, next ]
		7. when collision occurs, then a linkedlist is created on same index & elements are stored.
		8. maximum 8 collisions are allowed to create linked list in a single index, if collisions > 8, A bucket is converted to a Red‑Black Tree, ONLY IF:
				Bucket size >= 8  or HashMap capacity >= 64.  If capacity < 64 → resize instead of treeify. when resizing happen "threshold = capacity × loadFactor".

26. what is context switching? 
    	Context switching occurs when the OS switches the CPU from executing one process/thread to another. During this switch, the OS saves the execution context (CPU registers,
		program counter, stack pointer, flags.) of the current process/thread and restores the saved context of the next one to resume execution. This saving and restoring
		takes time → context switching is not free. This mechanism enables: Multitasking, Concurrency, Efficient CPU utilization.
		
		Real‑World Example, Consider a web server:
			Thread A is processing a request
			Thread A waits for DB response (I/O)
			OS switches CPU to Thread B
			When DB response arrives, OS switches back to Thread A
	    ✅ This switch is context switching.

27. Compare Wait()  and Sleep()
    both wait() and sleep() methods are used for pausing the execution of a thread, but they have different behaviors:

    wait() : When a thread calls the wait() method on an object, it releases the lock on the object and enters the waiting state until another thread notifies it 
             calling the notify() or notifyAll() method on the same object. The wait() method must be called from within a synchronized block/method to avoid 
             IllegalMonitorStateException.  it is defined in the Object class and is used for inter thread communication.

    sleep() : When a thread calls the sleep() method, it does not release the lock on any object, and other threads cannot acquire the lock during the sleep period.
                The sleep() method is typically used for introducing delays in the execution of a thread. The sleep() method is a static method defined in the 
                Thread class and is used to pause the execution of a thread for a specified amount of time.

    notify(): used to wake up a single thread that is waiting on the object. If multiple threads are waiting on the object, only one of them will be chosen
