36. how to handle Thread Interruptions
	The Core Principle: Interruption is a Request: you cannot force a thread to stop. Calling thread.interrupt() simply sets a boolean flag (the "interrupt status") on 
		the target thread. It is the responsibility of the code running inside that thread to check the flag and shut down gracefully.
	How to Handle it Properly
		Pattern A: Propagate the Exception: If you are writing a utility method and a blocking call (like Thread.sleep() or BlockingQueue.take()) throws an
			InterruptedException, the best practice is to not catch it at all. Let the caller decide how to handle the shutdown.
		Pattern B: Restore the Interrupt Status: In Spring Boot, you often cannot throw checked exceptions because you are overriding a method (like run()). 
			If you catch InterruptedException, you must not "swallow" it. You must restore the flag so higher-level frameworks (like Spring’s TaskExecutor) 
			know the thread was interrupted.

	Real-World Kafka Scenario: In a banking environment, a "hung" Kafka consumer can cause massive data lags. You use interruption to trigger a graceful shutdown of 
		the KafkaConsumer.poll().
	
	Interview Tip: Why "Restore" the Flag?
		An interviewer might ask: "Why do I need to call Thread.currentThread().interrupt() inside the catch block?"
		Answer: When a blocking method like Thread.sleep() throws an InterruptedException, it automatically clears the interrupt flag to false before throwing. 
				If I catch it and do nothing, the rest of the application won't know an interrupt was requested. By calling interrupt() again, I set the flag back to true, 
				allowing higher-level logic or thread pool managers to handle the cancellation properly."
	
37. What is ExecutorService
		ExecutorService manages a "pool" of threads and executes asynchronous tasks on background threads. You just give it the tasks, and it handles the execution, 
		reusing idle threads to save memory and CPU. It improves performance by reusing threads instead of creating new ones. It is part of the java.util.concurrent package. 
		Instead of creating threads manually, use the ExecutorService.

		1. How it Works Internally: An ExecutorService is a combination of a Thread Pool and a BlockingQueue. When you submit() a task, it goes to thread pool, 
			If all threads are busy, the task is placed in a Queue (usually a LinkedBlockingQueue). If the queue is also full, the Executor decides whether
			to create more threads or reject the task.
		2. The 4 Main Types of Thread Pools 
			Pool Type							Best Use Case							Behavior
			newFixedThreadPool				Kafka Consumers / DB writing		Constant number of threads. Safe for resource management.
			newCachedThreadPool				Short-lived asynchronous tasks		Creates new threads as needed; terminates idle threads after 60s.
			newSingleThreadExecutor			Sequential task processing			Guaranteed execution order one after another.
			newScheduledThreadPool			Cleanup jobs / Heartbeats			Can run tasks after a delay or periodically.

		3. What happens when the pool is full and the queue is also full? The ExecutorService uses a RejectedExecutionHandler with 4 standard policies(ABCD)
			AbortPolicy (Default): Throws an exception (RejectedExecutionException).
			CallerRunsPolicy: The thread that submitted the task (e.g., the Main thread) executes it itself. This slows down the producer, providing natural back-pressure.
			DiscardPolicy: Silently drops the task.
			DiscardOldestPolicy: Drops the oldest unhandled task to make room for the new one.

		4. Simply calling shutdown() isn't always enough in a production environment. You should use the "Two-Phase Shutdown" pattern to ensure data integrity:
					executor.shutdown(); 														// Phase 1: Stop accepting new tasks
						try {
    						if (!executor.awaitTermination(60, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {				// Wait a while for existing tasks to terminate
        						executor.shutdownNow(); 										// Phase 2: Cancel currently executing tasks
        						if (!executor.awaitTermination(60, TimeUnit.SECONDS)){			// Wait a while for tasks to respond to being cancelled
            						System.err.println("Pool did not terminate");
   								 }
							}
						} catch (InterruptedException ie) {
    						executor.shutdownNow(); 				// (Re-)Cancel if current thread also interrupted
    						Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
					}

