39. What is singleTon desing pattern
	The Singleton pattern is a creational design pattern that ensures a class has only one instance in the entire application and provides a global point of access to
	that instance. It’s commonly used for things like logging, configuration settings, cache managers, or thread pools
example: Thread-Safe Double-Checked Locking - To make singleton class thread safe, we use three key components:
	volatile keyword: Ensures that the change to instance is immediately visible to all threads and prevents "instruction reordering" by the compiler.
	Synchronized block: Only allows one thread to create the object at a time.
	Double-check: We check null twice—once outside the lock (for performance) and once inside (for safety).

public class SafeSingleton {
    private static volatile SafeSingleton instance;					// 1. volatile is mandatory for thread safety here

    private SafeSingleton() {
        System.out.println("Singleton Instance Created by: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }

    public static SafeSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {							        // First check (No locking, fast)
            synchronized (SafeSingleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {							// Second check (Inside lock, safe)
                    instance = new SafeSingleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}



